author: Emily Iannielli

text: Cricket used to be the national sport in the US before baseball surpassed it. In fact, the very first international cricket match was between the US and Canada before the game died out in both countries. Even George Washington played cricket with his men when he was a general. However, later the need to form an independent identity for the US and the need to distance itself from British culture, America saw cricket tying them too closely to the motherland. Baseball, contrary to popular belief, was also actually invented in England. Although it borrows heavily from cricket, it is most closely related to another British game called Rounders rather than to cricket itself.
author: Anton Zabinsky

text: But even though baseball was invented in England (supposedly by a man who also played some cricket), it was an unknown sport in Britain and therefore the US did not identify it as a British sport as such. Cricket was seen as too ingrained into the British culture, psyche at the time, so not ideal to keep it thriving in the US if it was to adopt a culture that was distinct from Britain.
author: Anton Zabinsky
